File Name: 01_basic_queries.sql

Description:
This SQL script contains a set of foundational queries used to explore and analyze
football match data from the Premier League dataset. The main purpose of this file
is to apply basic SQL techniques on a real-world dataset and answer simple but
meaningful analytical questions.


Objective:
The script was created as an introductory step in the project, focusing on the use
of standard SQL functions and basic query structures. It is designed to show how
raw football data can be transformed into useful information through simple analysis.


Topics Covered:
The queries in this file examine questions such as:
- How many matches, teams, and seasons are included in the dataset
- Which matches had the highest number of goals
- Which matches were the most intense based on cards received
- Which teams scored the most goals
- Which teams achieved the highest number of wins
- How match outcomes are distributed between home wins, away wins, and draws
- How goals are distributed across matches
- How the number of matches changes by year


SQL Concepts Used:
This file mainly uses simple and essential SQL concepts, including:
- SELECT
- COUNT
- SUM
- DISTINCT
- UNION / UNION ALL
- GROUP BY
- ORDER BY
- LIMIT
- CASE WHEN
- Basic date extraction with strftime()


Approach:
The goal was not only to practice SQL syntax, but also to answer real analytical
questions using football data. The script keeps the logic simple and readable, making
it suitable as a starting point for more advanced analysis in later files.


Results:
The output of these queries is stored separately in another folder. By reviewing the
results, anyone can identify useful patterns and draw conclusions about team
performance, scoring trends, match intensity, and outcome distribution.


Notes:
This file represents the first stage of the project and focuses on clear, structured,
and practical SQL analysis. It serves as the foundation for future expansion into
more advanced queries, deeper insights, and broader football data analytics.